After struggling through a flat economy in 2019, parents can expect the cost of private education in South Africa to escalate in 2020 – reaching record highs. The average fee hike among the 20 most expensive schools is around 7%. And as prices continue to climb, parents are starting to feel the pinch – with financial difficulties cited as one of the key reasons children are leaving private schools. Private school operators, such as AdvTech, in turn have had to change their operating strategies in this sector, namely a push into mid-market private schooling options. When BusinessTech first started tracking the most expensive schools in 2014, only one school (Hilton College) was priced over R200,000 for boarding and tuition – now in 2020, over 30 schools have moved into that price bracket. Hilton, and nearby MichaelHouse, have since pushed into the R300,000 per year bracket. In the 2019 listing of most expensive schools, 23 boarding schools exceeded R200,000 for the year, while 28 day schools had fees exceeding R100,000 annually. In the 2020 listing, this has jumped to 31 boarding schools, and 58 day schools, respectively. These are the 10 most expensive schools in 2020: Hilton College – R321,890 <img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-70073" src="https://businesstech.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/01-Hilton-College.png" alt="Hilton College" width="600" height="400" srcset="https://businesstech.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/01-Hilton-College.png 600w, https://businesstech.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/01-Hilton-College-300x200.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 709px) 85vw, (max-width: 909px) 67vw, (max-width: 984px) 61vw, (max-width: 1362px) 45vw, 600px" /> MichaelHouse – R303,600 <img class="aligncenter wp-image-87276" src="https://businesstech.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/Michaelhouse-Building.jpg" alt="Michaelhouse Building" width="604" height="402" srcset="https://businesstech.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/Michaelhouse-Buildin